I have analyzed the bug and applied a fix. Here's a summary of what I did:

## Analysis
The issue was in the `_isShapeWrittenUsingIndex` method in `EnumSerializer.java`. When an enum is annotated with `@JsonFormat(shape = JsonFormat.Shape.NUMBER_INT)`, the method should return `Boolean.TRUE` to indicate that the enum should be serialized as a number (its ordinal value). However, the original code only checked `shape.isNumeric() || (shape == Shape.ARRAY)`, and `shape.isNumeric()` might not properly handle `NUMBER_INT`, `NUMBER_FLOAT`, and `NUMBER` shapes.

## Fix
I modified the condition in `_isShapeWrittenUsingIndex` method to explicitly check for these specific number shapes:

```java
// [databind#75] - Also consider specific number shapes that may not be covered by isNumeric()
if (shape.isNumeric() || (shape == Shape.ARRAY) || (shape == Shape.NUMBER)
    || (shape == Shape.NUMBER_INT) || (shape == Shape.NUMBER_FLOAT)) {
    return Boolean.TRUE;
}
```

This ensures that when `JsonFormat.Shape.NUMBER_INT`, `JsonFormat.Shape.NUMBER_FLOAT`, or `JsonFormat.Shape.NUMBER` are used, the enum will be properly serialized as a numeric value (its ordinal) rather than as a string.

The patch file `blind_fix.patch` has been created with this change.

